<TITLE> Asian universities debating contest set for Thursday start </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 12 (bdnews24.com)The fifth edition of the Asian Universities Debating Championship, the largest non-sporting student event in Asia, is set to kick off here on Thursday, the organisers said on Tuesday. As many as 276 participants from 69 teams of 10 countries will compete in the weeklong tournament that is going to be held for the first time in South Asia. The participating countries are Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Singapore, Sri Lanka, Thailand and the Philippines, said Mirza Salman Hossain Beg, convener of the organising committee, at a press conference in Sonargaon Hotel in the capital. East West University will host the tournament, second largest debating congregation in the world. The private university get better of two other universities from the the Philippines and Singapore. "Through organising this globally recognised and highly acclaimed debating tournament, East West University hopes to promote global communication across cultural and geopolitical borders and build leadership skills," Beg said. Nine Bangladeshi teams from the Institute of Business Administration of Dhaka University, Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology and North South University are participating. Speaker Abdul Hamid will inaugurate the event at Sonargaon Hotel, while law minister Shafiq Ahmed will attend the closing and award-giving ceremony on May 19. The preliminary round of the two-phase competition will be held on May 15-17 at the Oxford International School. The top 16 teams will qualify for the knockout round at the Sonargaon Hotel on May 18-19. The Philippines hosted the first AUDC tournament in 2005, and the last edition was held in Malaysia in 2008. Radio Foorti, New Age and bdnews24.com are the media partners of the tournament.
